  "text": "When Grafana executes a log query to a Loki datasource, the HTTP call chain follows this path:\n\n1. **HTTP Client in Grafana** (grafana/grafana : pkg/tsdb/loki/api.go): The `LokiAPI` struct (defined at line 30) serves as the HTTP client for Loki queries. It contains an `*http.Client` field (line 31) that is used to send requests to Loki. The `DataQuery` method (line 167) orchestrates the query execution.\n\n2. **Request Construction** (grafana/grafana : pkg/tsdb/loki/api.go): The `makeDataRequest` function (line 48) constructs the HTTP request that will be sent to Loki. For instant queries (detected by `QueryTypeInstant`), it sets the request path to `/loki/api/v1/query` (line 88) and encodes query parameters like `query`, `limit`, `direction`, and `time` into the URL query string.\n\n3. **Request Transmission** (grafana/grafana : pkg/tsdb/loki/api.go): The `LokiAPI.DataQuery` method sends the constructed HTTP request using `api.client.Do(req)` at line 176, which executes the actual HTTP GET request to the Loki backend.\n\n4. **HTTP Parsing in Loki** (sg-evals/grafana-loki : pkg/loghttp/query.go): When Loki receives the instant query request, the `ParseInstantQuery` function (line 401) parses the incoming HTTP request. This function extracts the query parameters from the HTTP request, including `query` (the LogQL expression), `limit` (maximum result lines), `time` (the target timestamp), `direction` (backward/forward), and `shards` (optional shard specification), and returns an `InstantQuery` struct containing these parsed values.\n\nThis chain represents the complete path from Grafana's datasource plugin layer through to Loki's HTTP API parsing layer for instant log queries."
}

